
** Create AllocationMessenger

Add support for Allocation message + TODO for recovering from failure
  * Add com.ibm.aspen.core.allocation package
  * Add AllocationManager to drive the process
  * Need a "ClientAddress" to use for send/receive messages from non-store entity 
  * Can put error-recovery logic here as well (eventually)
  * Similar to Tx, each Alloc is driven by an object

Add support for Read Object
  * Add com.ibm.aspen.core.read package
  * Add ReadManager to track and drive progress
  * Similar to Tx and Alloc, each "Read" is driven similar to a Tx
  
Add DSL/STM support for Tx building
  
Figure out the allocation/bootstrapping issues

* Core package is message-handling centric.
  * only generated messages are in response to other messages
      |-> TransactionDriver subclasses are the only classes that generate messages and these will still
          generally only be responses. The only truly "generated" messages are from Paxos error recovery
          e.g. lost messages, leadership collisions, etc
          
  * network.MessageReceiver instance
     - dispatches messages to appropriate store.TransactionManager
         - dispatches to appropriate Transaction/TransactionDriver
  
* Transaction
   - Fills the Acceptor & Learner Paxos roles
   - Interacts with a DataStore to vote on whether or not a transaction should be committed
   - Interacts with the CrashRecovery Handler to ensure transaction state is not lost
   - Locks the object(s) to the Transaction if voting for commit
   - Ensures DataStore can CRL state is cleaned up when the transaction completes
    
* TransactionDriver
   - Fills Proposer & Learner roles Paxos.
   - Receives TxPrepared, TxAccepted and sends Prepare/Accept msgs
   - Created for designatedLeader nodes
   - Created for recovery of Tx with failed leader
   - Create via factory object passed to TxManager
   - Totally encapsulates the retransmit/retry logic
   		

  
* How to handle the data?
  * Want to allow it to live off-heap
  * No need to split it up in memory
  * LocalUpdates could be a BufferPointer,
      * Constructor reads buffer header to generate: List[(DataUpdateIndex,BufferOffset,Length)]
      
Mid-Term Enhancements:
* Add support for PrepareResponse messages received before corresponding Prepare message
      
      
BackLog
* Add detection & handling of leader failure

* Add detection and handling for Transaction recovery
   - While Tx is still in progress
   - After Tx commit/abort
   - After one or more objects have been updated *after* the Tx committed/aborted

* Add special messages for "PartiallyAccepted" and "SuccessfullyCommitted"
   |-> Use these in lieu of the normal messages if the crash recovery log is down. Peers use these to avoid
       adding recovery entries for transactions successfully processed.